Import Data and Analysis

data <- read.csv("Data_Group2.csv", header=T)[c("Date", "Switzerland.CHF.")]
head(data)
##         Date Switzerland.CHF.
## 1 31-01-1979            379.3
## 2 28-02-1979            413.6
## 3 30-03-1979            406.2
## 4 30-04-1979            420.0
## 5 31-05-1979            478.0
## 6 29-06-1979            457.7
price <- ts(data$Switzerland.CHF., start=c(1979, 1), end=c(2021, 7), frequency=12)
time <- time(price)
summary(price)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   379.3   501.6   698.2   826.1  1127.0  1787.5
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
ts.plot(price)
acf(price)

decompose.add <- decompose(price, type="additive")
decompose.mult <- decompose(price, type="multiplicative")
plot(decompose.add)

plot(decompose.mult)

From the time series plot and the ACF plot, we can see that there is significant trend in the data. We do not observe a seasonal component in the data. The time-series plot shows no sign of increasing variance. From the additive classic decomposition plot, we can see that the trend is significant, while seasonality is very weak, since it has a comparable range with the random component.

The Fligner-Killeen test result has a very small p-value, which rejects the hypothesis that our data has constant variance.

Hence, we conclude that our data is non-stationary with strong trend and non-constant variance.

Then, we split our data into training (90% of the data) and test sets (10% of the data).

training.price = window(price, start=c(1979,1), end=c(2017,3), frequency=12)
training.time = window(time, start=c(1979,1), end=c(2017,3), frequency=12)
test.price = window(price, start=c(2017, 3), frequency=12)
test.time = window(time, start=c(2017, 3), frequency=12)
test = data.frame(time=test.time)
training <- data.frame(price=training.price, time=training.time)
df <- data.frame(price=price, time=time)

reg.idx = sample(1:length(price), 53)
reg.training.price = price[-reg.idx]
reg.training.time = time[-reg.idx]
reg.test.price = price[reg.idx]
reg.test.time = time[reg.idx]
reg.train = data.frame(price=reg.training.price, time=reg.training.time)
reg.test = data.frame(time=reg.test.time)

Now, we will use power transformation to make variance constant.

library(MASS)
## non-constant variance
seg = factor(c(rep(1:4, each=90), rep(5, 99)))
fligner.test(training.price, seg)
## 
##  Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  training.price and seg
## Fligner-Killeen:med chi-squared = 80.736, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16
power.alpha <- c(-2,-1.5,-1,-0.5,0,0.5,1.5,2)
bx = boxcox(lm(training.price~1), lambda=power.alpha)

f.p <- c()
for (a in power.alpha) {
  if (a == 0) {
    y.star = log(training.price)
  } else {
    y.star = training.price^a
  }
  f.test = fligner.test(y.star, seg)
  f.p = c(f.p, f.test$p.value)
}
f.p
## [1] 3.663350e-26 3.285780e-21 1.120266e-16 1.339796e-12 1.706958e-11
## [6] 4.735416e-13 4.213607e-23 1.728053e-29
plot(f.p)
abline(h=0.1, col="red")

print(power.alpha[which(f.p>0.1)])
## numeric(0)
power.alpha.opt = bx$x[which.max(bx$y)]
training.price.star = training.price^power.alpha.opt
test.price.star = test.price^power.alpha.opt
price.star = price^power.alpha.opt
fligner.test(training.price.star, seg)
## 
##  Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  training.price.star and seg
## Fligner-Killeen:med chi-squared = 70.43, df = 4, p-value = 1.841e-14
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
ts.plot(training.price.star)
acf(training.price.star)

Regression

We will use polynomial regression (without regularization) first, and then Ridge, LASSO, and Elastic Net as regularized models to fit the model on the data.

degrees <- c(2:15)
MSE <- function(y, yhat) {
  mean((y-yhat)^2)
}
# create fit models with different degrees
poly.mse = c()
for (d in degrees) {
  model = lm(price ~ poly(as.vector(time), d), data=reg.train)
  pred = predict.lm(model, reg.test, interval = "none")
  mse = MSE(reg.test.price, pred)
  poly.mse = c(poly.mse, mse)
}
print(data.frame(degree=degrees, MSE=poly.mse))
##    degree       MSE
## 1       2 43962.031
## 2       3 41332.929

## 10     11  9733.124
## 11     12  9744.475
## 12     13  9421.467
## 13     14  9504.338
## 14     15  8923.381
poly.opt = degrees[which.min(poly.mse)]
plot(degrees, poly.mse)

print(paste("Degree of the most optimal polynomial is: ", poly.opt))
## [1] "Degree of the most optimal polynomial is:  15"
poly.model = lm(price ~ poly(as.vector(time), poly.opt), data=df)

We can see that the fitted and predicted values fit pretty well in the data. Since the degree of 14 is pretty high, we might face the issue of over-fitting.

Therefore, we try to fit the model by regression with regularization, i.e. Ridge, LASSO, or Elastic Net models, and use a 10-fold cross validation to find the best degree and \(\lambda\) value.

library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-4
# possible lambda values
Log.Lambda.Seq = c(seq(-10,10,by=0.5)) 
Lambda.Seq = exp(Log.Lambda.Seq)
set.seed(443)

## RIDGE
lambda.ridge = c()
CV.ridge.error = c()
for (p in degrees) {
  X = poly(as.vector(time), degree=p, simple=T)
  CV = cv.glmnet(X, as.vector(price), alpha=0, lambda=Lambda.Seq, 
                 standardize = T, family = "gaussian")
  lambda.ridge = c(lambda.ridge, CV$lambda.min)
  CV.ridge.error = c(CV.ridge.error, CV$cvm[CV$index[1,1]])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(degrees, lambda.ridge)
plot(degrees, CV.ridge.error)

degree.ridge.opt = degrees[which.min(CV.ridge.error)]
lambda.ridge.opt = lambda.ridge[which.min(CV.ridge.error)]
sprintf("The best ridge model is at degree %d with lambda %.4f", degree.ridge.opt, lambda.ridge.opt)
## [1] "The best ridge model is at degree 15 with lambda 0.2231"
## LASSO
lambda.lasso = c()
CV.lasso.error = c()
for (p in degrees) {
  X = poly(as.vector(time), degree=p, simple=T)
  CV = cv.glmnet(X, as.vector(price), alpha=1, lambda=Lambda.Seq, 
                 standardize = T, family = "gaussian")
  lambda.lasso = c(lambda.lasso, CV$lambda.min)
  CV.lasso.error = c(CV.lasso.error, CV$cvm[CV$index[1,1]])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(degrees, lambda.lasso)
plot(degrees, CV.lasso.error)

degree.lasso.opt = degrees[which.min(CV.lasso.error)]
lambda.lasso.opt = lambda.lasso[which.min(CV.lasso.error)]
sprintf("The best lasso model is at degree %d with lambda %.4f", degree.lasso.opt, lambda.lasso.opt)
## [1] "The best lasso model is at degree 15 with lambda 0.3679"
## ELASTIC NET
lambda.elastic = c()
CV.elastic.error = c()
for (p in degrees) {
  X = poly(as.vector(time), degree=p, simple=T)
  CV = cv.glmnet(X, as.vector(price), alpha=0.5, lambda=Lambda.Seq, 
                 standardize = T, family = "gaussian")
  lambda.elastic = c(lambda.elastic, CV$lambda.min)
  CV.elastic.error = c(CV.elastic.error, CV$cvm[CV$index[1,1]])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(degrees, lambda.elastic)
plot(degrees, CV.elastic.error)

degree.elastic.opt = degrees[which.min(CV.elastic.error)]
lambda.elastic.opt = lambda.elastic[which.min(CV.elastic.error)]
sprintf("The best elastic model is at degree %d with lambda %.4f", degree.elastic.opt, lambda.elastic.opt)
## [1] "The best elastic model is at degree 15 with lambda 1.6487"
ridge.time = poly(as.vector(time), degree=degree.ridge.opt, simple=T)
ridge.model = glmnet(ridge.time, as.vector(price), alpha=0, lambda=lambda.ridge.opt, 
                     standardize = T, family = "gaussian")
lasso.time = poly(as.vector(time), degree=degree.lasso.opt, simple=T)
lasso.model = glmnet(lasso.time, as.vector(price), alpha=1, lambda = lambda.lasso.opt,
                     standardize = T, family="gaussian")
elastic.time = poly(as.vector(time), degree=degree.elastic.opt, simple=T)
elastic.model = glmnet(elastic.time, as.vector(price), alpha=0.5, lambda=lambda.elastic.opt, 
                       standardize = T, family = "gaussian")

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.model, ridge.time, type="response")
ridge.mse = MSE(price, ridge.pred)
lasso.pred = predict(lasso.model, lasso.time, type="response")
lasso.mse = MSE(price, lasso.pred)
elastic.pred = predict(elastic.model, elastic.time, type="response")
elastic.mse = MSE(price, elastic.pred)

all = data.frame(polynomial=poly.MSE, ridge=ridge.mse, lasso=lasso.mse, elastic=elastic.mse)
all
##   polynomial    ridge    lasso  elastic
## 1   5782.786 5782.833 5784.685 5796.251
ts.plot(price)
points(time, poly.pred, col="green", type="l")
points(time, ridge.pred, col="blue",type='l')
points(time, lasso.pred, col="red", type='l')
points(time, elastic.pred, col="orange", type='l')

Comparing all the regression models, we see that the ridge regression works the best. We’ll do a residual analysis to see if the model assumptions are met.

res = price - ridge.pred
par(mfrow=c(5,1))
plot(price, poly.pred, xlab="Observed values", ylab="Fitted values")
abline(coef = c(0,1), col="red")
plot(poly.pred, res, xlab="Fitted values", ylab="Residuals")
abline(h=0, col="red")
plot(res, ylab="Residuals")
abline(h=0, col="red")
car::qqPlot(res, pch=16, col=adjustcolor("black", 0.7),
            xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles (Normal)",
            ylab = "Sample Quantiles (r.hat)",
            main = "Normal Q-Q Plot")
## [1] 405  39
acf(res, lag.max=100, main="Sample ACF of Residuals")

From the plots, we see that the residuals are not normal (Q-Q plot) and has trend (linear decay in ACF). There is no correlation between the residuals with the fitted values.

We can perform more tests to confirm the results:

# shapiro-wilk
shapiro.test(res)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  res
## W = 0.98733, p-value = 0.0002035
# constant variance
seg = c(rep(1:4, each=102), rep(5, 103))
fligner.test(res, seg)
## 
##  Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  res and seg
## Fligner-Killeen:med chi-squared = 112.35, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16
# difference sign test
randtests::difference.sign.test(res)
## 
##  Difference Sign Test
## 
## data:  res
## statistic = -0.61237, n = 511, p-value = 0.5403
## alternative hypothesis: nonrandomness
# run tests
lawstat::runs.test(res)
## 
##  Runs Test - Two sided
## 
## data:  res
## Standardized Runs Statistic = -16.96, p-value < 2.2e-16

We can see that the residuals are not normal, have non-constant variance, and not random.

Differencing

#one regular differencing
diff1 = diff(training.price)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(diff1, main="First-order regular differencing")
hist(diff1)
acf(diff1, lag.max = 60)
pacf(diff1, lag.max = 60)

Based on the acf, there is no obvious trend, and the data becomes stationary.

d = 1 \[ Y_t = \nabla X_t = (1-B)X_t = X_t - X_{t-1} \] There are no significant seasonal lags in acf and pacf.
